A helpful FERC order as we work on asset management deals:

New Horizon Electric Cooperative Inc. v. Duke Power Company, EL00-101-001.=20
Order on Rehearing. Order issued October 11, 2000 addressing a complaint by=20
New Horizon Electric Cooperative, Inc (New Horizon) against Duke Power Co.=20
(Duke) seeking FERC resolution of four disputed issues, including treatment=20
of energy imbalances not prevented by dynamic scheduling. New Horizon's=20
complaint claimed that energy imbalance service does not apply to it, since=20
it will employ dynamic scheduling to effectively remove its load from Duke's=
=20
control area. Further, New Horizon maintained that any deviation between the=
=20
dynamic schedule and the actual metered delivery of energy constituted=20
inadvertent interchange energy (which is the net difference between actual=20
and scheduled interchange energy between two control areas) and proposed tha=
t=20
any differences would be returned in-kind within two hours. On November 9,=20
New Horizon filed a request for rehearing or clarification of the October 11=
=20
Order. Order issued February 26 granting New Horizon's request for rehearing=
=20
or clarification of the October 11 Order. Order clarifies that, to the exten=
t=20
dynamic scheduling by New Horizon operates successfully; New Horizon should=20
not be subject to charges under Duke's Schedule 4 Energy Imbalance Service.=20
In such circumstances, any imbalances between energy deliveries on behalf of=
=20
New Horizon and New Horizon's load should be accounted for by Duke as=20
inadvertent interchanges only. In addition, Order directed parties to=20
negotiate in good faith to establish a standard for the successful operation=
=20
of dynamic scheduling.


